note.p: The collation in this catalogue record deviates from the collation provided by James (1901) and a modern librarian who has added quire numbers the lower outer corners of the first rectos of quires. Whereas James identifies Quire 1 as a quinternion with 10 missing, this catalogue record notes the presence of a catchword on f. 9v and identifies it as a quaternion with one added leaf at the beginning (also suggested by the fact that f. 1 appears to be made of a thicker parchment). Whereas James identifies Quire 17 as consisting of 6 leaves, this catalogue record notes the presence of a stub after 5, indicating that there is a missing leaf. Consequently, it identifies the start of Quire 18 at f. 127 and not f. 128 as James does. While James states that Quire 18 is a quaternion, this catalogue record, noting the presence of thread tackets between f. 131 and f. 132 and f. 136 and f. 137, identifies it as a quinternion with an added bifolium between f. 135 and f. 138. Consequently, the quire numbers in this catalogue record are always one behind those provided by James and the modern librarian. Finally, this catalogue record also does not recognise the absence of a quire between the second to last and last quires: where James jumps from Quire 27 to Quire 29, the collation in this catalogue record progresses from Quire 26 to Quire 27.

Like James, this catalogue record identifies five distinct parts in the manuscript but it disagrees with the ranges provided for the codicological units: whereas James places the end of Part 2 at f. 131, this catalogue record places it at f. 126.
Quire numbers added by a modern hand in pencil to the lower outer corners of the first rectos of quires.

binding.p: 17th- or 18th-century brown leather over pasteboards; the spine gold-tooled and with a red leather label with the gold-stamped inscription: CHIRURGYA ROGERI GUISCHARDI

provenance.p: Thomas Curteys [Curtes] (fl. late 15th or 16th century) Curteys [Curtes], Thomas, fl. late 15th or 16th century: his ownership inscription: This boke ded Thomas Curtes bey off the parsun off hoptuns brother Record of Eglyn of bovrgate (f. 2r); and his signature or name inscription: Curtays (f. 2r).

John By[n]es (fl. 16th century) By[n]es, John, fl. 16th century and John [S]mere (fl. 16th century) [S]mere, John, fl. 16th century: Their names inscribed on f. 1r: John By[n]es - John [S]mere Servaunts to John Wa[...]. Mooney (1995), p. 31 transcribes the first name as John Beyers.

John Wilson (d. 1754) Wilson, John, d. 1754, Fellow of Trinity College, tutor, senior bursar, vicar of Over and Chesterton: given by him to Trinity College as inscribed on f. 1r: For Trinity College Library - John Wilson.

acquisition.p: Bequeathed to Cambridge, Trinity College, by John Wilson (d. 1754) Wilson, John, d. 1754 in 1754. The College's current classmark (R.14.32) is inscribed in pencil on the inside of the upper cover, once more below that in red pencil, and in brown ink on f. 1r. The alpha-numerical elements are printed separately onto three paper labels pasted onto the spine. Its ex libris, featuring an engraving of its heraldic arms, motto (Virtus Vera Nobilitas), and name Coll: Trin: Cantab:) by William Stephens, fl. c. 1740-c. 1760 (Stephens sculp.) pasted onto the inside of the upper cover. A smaller printed ex libris has been pasted onto f. 1r.

Mooney, Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College, Cambridge, The Index of Middle English Prose, Handlist XI (Woodbridge: Brewer, 1995).

msItem.title: Glosulae guatuor magistrorum super chirurgiam Rogerii et Rolandi (Prologue)
msItem.author: The Four Masters (medical glossators)
msItem.incipit: 1v Ut testantur omnes auctores tria sunt instrumenta per que medicus debet operari
msItem.explicit: 2r (lower margin) Et nos habemus regulam generalem ab omnibus auctoribus quod omnis motus contrarius est consolidationi et sic impossibile est cerebrum pulmonem et cor quantum ad interiores
msItem.note: The the text is written in two columns on f. 1v and continues in the lower margin of f. 2r. Evidently, it was intended as a marginal text for the Practica Chirurgiae [Chirurgia] of Ruggero Frugardo [Roger Frugardi, Rogerius Salernitanus, Roger of Parma] but the text breaks of abruptly and does not continue beyond f. 2r.

msItem.title: Prologue to the Practica Chirurgiae [Chirurgia]

msItem.incipit: 2r Post mundi fabricam eiusque decorem de terrestri substancia deus hominem formauit uite
msItem.explicit: 3v Que ab ea parte recepit uocabulum. curas ergo capitis sicut dignioris prius prosequamur; singula capitula huius particule pro sequi debemus per ordinem prescribendo
msItem.note: The opening of the text is accompanied by a marginal gloss on the etymology of the word cyrurgia: Cyrurgia dicitur a cyros quod est manus et agy grece quod est actio latine . quasi actio manualis eo guod et si\sti/t in operatione manuum.
The work is divided in four books: Book 1 begins at f. 6v; Book 2 beings at f. 46r; Book 3 beings at f. 68v; and Book 4 begins at f. 105r.

msItem.title: French Kalendar with additions for Oxford, 1337-1344
msItem.textLang: Latin with additions in Latin and Middle French
msItem.note: For transcriptions and discussions of the Kalendar, see James (1901), pp. 312-314, and Wordsworth (1904), pp. xiii-xxxii. Among the 14th-century additions are feasts and anniversaries for saints and historic figures from the British Isles, including: St Brigid of Kildare (1 February); Translation of St Frideswide (12 February); Ela LongespÃ©e, Countess of Warwick (d. 9 February 1298): Missa pro anima domine ele de longespeie; St Chad (2 March); ? Philip de Turville, canon of Lichfield: Missa pro anima magistri Philippi Turuel et sunt ordinaciones (2 March); Henry de Guldeford Missa pro h. de guldeforde (12 March); St Patrick (17 March); St Edward the Martyr (18 March); St Cuthbert (20 March); St Richard of Chichester (3 April); Walter de Gray, Archbishop of York (1 May): missa pro W. gay; Ob. Reginaldi Bedelli (10 May); missa pro Gilberto de Roubiry (13 May); Invencio Sancte Frideswide (18 May); St Aldhelm (25 May); Missa pro Gilberto de Sancto Leopardo (25 May) Translation of St Edmund the Martyr (9 June); St Richard of Chichester (16 June); Henry Harclay (25 June), philosopher and chancellor of the University of Oxford; Missa pro .h. Herclay St Edward the Confessor (13 October); St Frideswide (19 October); Missa pro W. le Gray (12 November); St Edmund of Abingdon (16 November); St Hugh of Lincoln (17 November); St Edmund the Martyr (20 November); Missa pro Ela com. (23 November); John of Pointoise, Bishop of Winchester (5 December): Missa pro Johanne de Pontois; Missa pro henr. de Lacy (17 December). Eleanor of Castile (30 November): Missa pro Elianora regina. A later (15th-century) hand has added the following entry in June: Johannes de Bofis cordeweuer [James (1901): cordewener] deuant la mostre en chaudebeke.
